text:
Heyyy folks! Hopefully this is a fun conversation starter: Looking for the best industry newsletters that you _actually read_ and look forward to, particularly around the following topics:
• remote work and culture
• productivity
• b2b tech, or tech generally
We’re looking into partnerships and sponsoring of newsletters (has anyone done this before and willing to share tips?) Personally, I love niche Substacks from people who are genuine experts about their subject matter :nerd_face:

text: I'd also add that sometimes you're walking into an org with a ton of legacy/existing content. And sometimes you're starting from scratch. So even if you're not inheriting a _mess_, you might be inheriting content created under a 2010 strategy and your challenge is to figure out what to do with all of that content and how to steward into 2021. :slightly_smiling_face:

text: I've found that sometimes building this process is about earning trust. When SMEs see that you made other people sound really good, they're more willing to raise their hand. It's about showing them that they can put in minimal effort (a 30-minute focused interview) and reap the benefits of the content you produce. They want to look good, and you're helping them do that. :upside_down_face:

text: I'm a huge fan of using illustration for B2B tech clients, but this article hits the nail on the head of the challenge of getting clients (even big ones) to invest the dollars it takes to develop custom illustration. And that hesitance has created some unfortunate homogeneity in the industry. Interested to hear your thoughts on how we can do illustration better in our B2B content design. Or should we go back to (dreaded) stock photos? <https://www.protocol.com/workplace/why-is-tech-illustration-stuck-on-repeat-ask-the-overworked-underpaid-illustrators>

attachments.service_name: Protocol — The people, power and politics of tech
attachments.title: Why is tech illustration stuck on repeat?
attachments.text: Freelance illustrators are overworked and underpaid — few stay in the career beyond their 30s. Yet they craft the public images for many of the world’s most powerful companies. What gives?
